\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. E. orientale} (L.) Jaub. & Spach,{\i  Ill. Pl. Or.}{\b  4}: 26 (1851). Stems up to 25 cm. Leaves 3-6 cm × 2-3 mm, scabridulous, sometimes puberulent on the upper surface. Spike up to 2·5 cm × 9-15 mm, dense, elliptic-ovate; rhachis fragile. Spikelets 10-15 mm, divergent from the rhachis, usually with 2-3 florets. Glumes 10-15 mm (including awns), lanceolate, asymmetrical, with 2-3 conspicuous marginal veins, strongly curved, hispid on the sides, with an awn 2-5 mm. Lemma as long as or slightly longer than the glumes, hispidulous, with an awn 4-5 mm. Keels of the palea prolonged into 2 tooth-like appendages. 2n = 28. {\i Steppes and semi-deserts. S.E. Europe, from E. Romania to W. Kazakhstan.} Rm Rs (C, W, K, E).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. E. distans} (C. Koch) Nevski, {\i Acta Univ. As. Med.} ser. 8b (Bot.), {\b 17}: 52 (1934). Stems up to 25 cm. Leaves 6-8 cm × 2-3 mm, scabrid, sometimes-sparsely hairy on the upper surface, glabrous beneath. Spike 2·5-5 cm × 8-15 mm, dense; rhachis very fragile. Spikelets 15-17 mm, more or less suberect, with 3-5(-6) florets. Glumes 13-17 mm (including awns), narrowly lanceolate, with 2-3 obscure marginal veins, slightly curved, villous on sides; awn 6-7 mm. Lemma as long as or slightly longer than the glumes, densely villous, with an awn 5-7 mm. Keels of the palea prolonged into 2 tooth-like appendages. 2n = 14, 28.{\i  Stony, sandy or clayey slopes. S.E. Russia.} Rs (E). ({\i S.W. & S.C. Asia; Algeria.})
